summary: The document is an FBI identification form related to the JFK assassination, detailing John Rosselli's movements and associations. It notes his arrival in Los Angeles from Florida on October 26, 1962, without being listed on the passenger manifest, his transportation to Beverly Hills in a yellow cab, and his connections to individuals such as Judith E. Campbell and Sam Giancana. Additionally, it mentions a financial transaction involving Rosselli and a check from Rothman and Hamilton's client trust account, as well as his association with Harry Drucker's barbershop. The document, part of the FBI's records on the JFK assassination, was released with certain deletions.
key_findings: John Rosselli arrived in Los Angeles on October 26, 1962, from Florida, but was not listed on the passenger manifest.
Rosselli was transported from the airport to Beverly Hills, California, in a yellow cab.
Rosselli is associated with Harry Drucker's barbershop and received a check from Rothman and Hamilton's client trust account.
Judith E. Campbell, a friend of Rosselli and Sam Giancana, was residing in Palm Springs, California, at the time.
The document is part of the FBI's records on the JFK assassination and was released with deletions.
